tooltip.HIGH: Score combiné élevé (≥0.8) signifie souvent que le SNV est à la fois suffisamment rare/dommageable et correspond au phénotype.

tooltip.PVS1: Null variant (nonsense, frameshift, canonical ± 1 or 2 splice sites, initiation codon, single or multiexon deletion) in a gene where LOF (loss of function) is a known mechanism of disease.
tooltip.PS1: Same amino acid change as a previously established pathogenic variant regardless of nucleotide change.
tooltip.PS2: De novo (both maternity and paternity confirmed) in a patient with the disease and no family history.
tooltip.PS3: Well-established in vitro or in vivo functional studies supportive of a damaging effect on the gene or gene product.
tooltip.PS4: The prevalence of the variant in affected individuals is significantly increased compared with the prevalence in controls.
tooltip.PM1: Located in a mutational hot spot and/or critical and well-established functional domain (e.g., active site of an enzyme) without benign variation.
tooltip.PM2: Absent from controls (or at extremely low frequency if recessive) in Exome Sequencing Project, 1000 Genomes Project, or Exome Aggregation Consortium.
tooltip.PM3: For recessive disorders, detected in trans with a pathogenic variant.
tooltip.PM4: Protein length changes as a result of in-frame deletions/insertions in a nonrepeat region or stop-loss variants.
tooltip.PM5: Novel missense change at an amino acid residue where a different missense change determined to be pathogenic has been seen before.
tooltip.PM6: Assumed de novo, but without confirmation of paternity and maternity.
tooltip.PP1: Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease.
tooltip.PP2: Missense variant in a gene that has a low rate of benign missense variation and in which missense variants are a common mechanism of disease.
tooltip.PP3: Multiple lines of computational evidence support a deleterious effect on the gene or gene product (conservation, evolutionary, splicing impact, etc.).
tooltip.PP4: Patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.
tooltip.PP5: Reputable source recently reports variant as pathogenic, but the evidence is not available to the laboratory to perform an independent evaluation.
tooltip.BA1: Allele frequency is >5% in Exome Sequencing Project, 1000 Genomes Project, or Exome Aggregation Consortium.
tooltip.BS1: Allele frequency is greater than expected for disorder.
tooltip.BS2: Observed in a healthy adult individual for a recessive (homozygous), dominant (heterozygous), or X-linked (hemizygous) disorder.
tooltip.BS3: Well-established in vitro or in vivo functional studies show no damaging effect on the gene or gene product.
tooltip.BS4: The prevalence of the variant in affected individuals is significantly decreased compared with the prevalence in controls.
tooltip.BP1: Missense variant in a gene for which primarily truncating variants are known to cause disease.
tooltip.BP2: Observed in-trans with a pathogenic variant for a fully penetrant dominant gene/disorder.
tooltip.BP3: In-frame deletions/insertions in a repetitive region without a known function.
tooltip.BP4: Multiple lines of computational evidence suggest no impact on gene or gene product (conservation, evolutionary, splicing impact, etc.).
tooltip.BP5: Variant found in a case with an alternate molecular basis for disease.
tooltip.BP6: Reputable source recently reports variant as benign, but the evidence is not available to the laboratory to perform an independent evaluation.
tooltip.BP7: A synonymous (silent) variant for which splicing prediction algorithms predict no impact to the splice consensus sequence nor the creation of a new splice site.
